# Next.js 16 Anti-Patterns

Reject these in generated code. Each entry has a BAD example and the CORRECT replacement. Severity tags map to the reviewer agent's grouping.

> Target: `next` 16.0+ on `react` 19.2+. Many of these patterns were valid in earlier versions and the LLM may have learned them from 2023-2024 training data. The "Replaced in" / "Removed in" tags on each entry tell you when the BAD form stopped working.

## 1. `getServerSideProps` / `getStaticProps` / `getInitialProps` **CRITICAL**

Pages Router data-fetching APIs. They do not exist in App Router.

```typescript
// BAD - Pages Router, will not run in App Router
export async function getServerSideProps() {
  return { props: { posts: await fetchPosts() } };
}
export default function Page({ posts }: { posts: Post[] }) { /* ... */ }

// CORRECT - async Server Component fetches directly
export default async function Page() {
  const posts = await fetchPosts();
  return <PostList posts={posts} />;
}
```

`pages/api/*.ts` Route handlers are also Pages Router. Use `app/api/<path>/route.ts` with named-export `GET`/`POST`/etc.

## 2. `'use client'` on a layout or page **ERROR**

A `'use client'` directive at the top of a layout or page makes the entire subtree client-rendered. You lose Server Components for everything below.

```typescript
// BAD - this layout forces every page underneath to be client
'use client';
export default function Layout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return <div>{children}</div>;
}

// CORRECT - keep the layout server-side, extract the interactive sliver
// app/(dashboard)/layout.tsx (Server Component, no directive)
export default function Layout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <div>
      <Sidebar /> {/* small Client Component for interactivity */}
      <main>{children}</main>
    </div>
  );
}

// app/(dashboard)/_components/sidebar.tsx
'use client';
export function Sidebar() { /* useState, onClick, etc. */ }
```

Push `'use client'` as far down the tree as possible. The directive sets a *boundary* - everything imported from that file forward is client.

## 3. `useEffect` + `fetch` for server data **ERROR**

Client-side fetch in a `useEffect` for data that has no per-user interactive reason to live on the client. Doubles the trip (server -> HTML -> client -> fetch -> hydrate) and loses streaming.

```typescript
// BAD
'use client';
export function Posts() {
  const [posts, setPosts] = useState<Post[]>([]);
  useEffect(() => {
    fetch('/api/posts').then(r => r.json()).then(setPosts);
  }, []);
  return <PostList posts={posts} />;
}

// CORRECT - Server Component, fetch happens during render
export default async function Posts() {
  const posts = await fetchPosts(); // direct DB or DAL call
  return <PostList posts={posts} />;
}
```

Use SWR/TanStack Query for genuinely client-side dynamic data (live polling, mutation-driven cache, optimistic updates). For "load once on render," it's a Server Component.

## 4. Sync `cookies()` / `headers()` / `draftMode()` **CRITICAL**

These have been async since Next.js 15. In v16 the sync form is fully removed - direct access is a TypeScript error.

```typescript
// BAD - TypeError in v16
import { cookies } from 'next/headers';
export default function Page() {
  const theme = cookies().get('theme')?.value;
  return <div data-theme={theme}>...</div>;
}

// CORRECT
import { cookies } from 'next/headers';
export default async function Page() {
  const cookieStore = await cookies();
  const theme = cookieStore.get('theme')?.value;
  return <div data-theme={theme}>...</div>;
}
```

Same shape for `headers()` and `draftMode()`. Codemod available: `npx @next/codemod@canary upgrade latest`.

## 5. Sync `params` / `searchParams` **CRITICAL**

Page, layout, and route-handler `params` and `searchParams` are Promises in v16.

```typescript
// BAD - TypeError in v16
export default function Page({ params }: { params: { slug: string } }) {
  return <article>{params.slug}</article>;
}

// CORRECT
export default async function Page({ params }: { params: Promise<{ slug: string }> }) {
  const { slug } = await params;
  return <article>{slug}</article>;
}

// CORRECT (typed via next typegen) - run `next typegen` once
import type { PageProps } from 'next';
export default async function Page({ params }: PageProps<'/blog/[slug]'>) {
  const { slug } = await params;
  return <article>{slug}</article>;
}
```

`generateMetadata`, `route.ts` handlers, and `opengraph-image.tsx` generators all receive async `params` too. The `id` in `generateImageMetadata` is also async in v16 (was sync in v15).

## 6. `fetch()` cached by default assumption **ERROR**

Starting with Next.js 15, `fetch()` is **not** cached by default. With `cacheComponents: true` enabled (v16), nothing is cached unless you opt in via the `'use cache'` directive, `cacheLife`, or `cacheTag`.

```typescript
// BAD - assumes 14.x cached-by-default behavior, gets fresh fetches every time
async function getPrices() {
  const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com/prices');
  return res.json();
}

// CORRECT - opt in to cache explicitly
async function getPrices() {
  'use cache';
  cacheLife('hours');
  cacheTag('prices');
  const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com/prices');
  return res.json();
}

// OR - per-call revalidate
async function getPrices() {
  const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com/prices', {
    next: { revalidate: 3600, tags: ['prices'] },
  });
  return res.json();
}
```

## 7. `useFormState` (deprecated) **ERROR**

Renamed to `useActionState` in React 19 and moved from `react-dom` to `react`. The signature gained a third tuple element for pending state.

```typescript
// BAD - deprecated since React 19
import { useFormState } from 'react-dom';
const [state, formAction] = useFormState(action, initialState);

// CORRECT - React 19+
import { useActionState } from 'react';
const [state, formAction, isPending] = useActionState(action, initialState);
```

`experimental_useFormState` was never stable - same fix.

## 8. Missing `useFormStatus` for pending UI on submit buttons **WARN**

`useActionState` gives you the *result* pending state. For visual feedback on the submit button itself (especially when the button is a child component), use `useFormStatus`. It still lives in `react-dom` and only works inside a child of a `<form>`.

```typescript
// BAD - no pending indicator, user double-clicks submit
'use client';
export function SubmitButton() {
  return <button type="submit">Save</button>;
}

// CORRECT
'use client';
import { useFormStatus } from 'react-dom';
export function SubmitButton() {
  const { pending } = useFormStatus();
  return (
    <button type="submit" disabled={pending}>
      {pending ? 'Saving...' : 'Save'}
    </button>
  );
}
```

## 9. `revalidateTag(tag)` single-arg form **ERROR**

In v16 the recommended form of `revalidateTag` takes a cache profile as the second argument (a name like `'max'` / `'hours'` / `'days'`, or an inline `{ expire: number }`). The single-arg form is deprecated. Depending on your installed patch and TS settings it surfaces as either a TypeScript error or a runtime deprecation - treat it as an error and always pass the profile.

```typescript
// BAD - deprecated in v16
revalidateTag('posts');

// CORRECT - explicit profile
revalidateTag('posts', 'max');                  // never expires after refresh
revalidateTag('posts', { expire: 3600 });       // inline override

// ALTERNATIVE - within a Server Action where you want read-your-writes
updateTag('posts'); // expires + refreshes within the same request
```

## 10. `middleware.ts` for new code **WARN**

The middleware file was renamed `proxy.ts` in v16, with the named export changing from `middleware` to `proxy`. `middleware.ts` still works for the Edge runtime use case but is deprecated. `proxy.ts` runs on the Node.js runtime only.

```typescript
// BAD (new code) - middleware.ts
// middleware.ts
import { NextResponse } from 'next/server';
import type { NextRequest } from 'next/server';
export function middleware(req: NextRequest) {
  return NextResponse.next();
}

// CORRECT - proxy.ts
// proxy.ts
import { NextResponse } from 'next/server';
import type { NextRequest } from 'next/server';
export function proxy(req: NextRequest) {
  return NextResponse.next();
}
```

Config flag renamed too: `skipMiddlewareUrlNormalize` → `skipProxyUrlNormalize`. See the `nextjs-proxy-and-auth` rule for the full pattern.

## 11. `experimental.ppr` / `experimental.dynamicIO` / `experimental.useCache` flags **ERROR**

All three were collapsed into the single top-level `cacheComponents: true` flag in v16. Setting any of the old flags is now a config error.

```typescript
// BAD - v15 experimental flags
// next.config.ts
const config = {
  experimental: { ppr: true, dynamicIO: true, useCache: true },
};

// CORRECT - v16
const config = {
  cacheComponents: true,
};
```

The route-level `export const experimental_ppr = true` directive is also removed. Cache Components is the unified opt-in.

## 12. `redirect()` inside `try / catch` **CRITICAL**

`redirect()` works by throwing `NEXT_REDIRECT`. A `try / catch` block intercepts that throw and the redirect silently dies.

```typescript
// BAD - the catch swallows the redirect throw
'use server';
export async function createPost(formData: FormData) {
  try {
    await db.post.create({ data: { /* ... */ } });
    redirect('/posts');  // <-- thrown, then caught below
  } catch (e) {
    console.error(e);    // logs "NEXT_REDIRECT", nothing happens
  }
}

// CORRECT - call redirect AFTER the try/catch returns successfully
'use server';
export async function createPost(formData: FormData) {
  try {
    await db.post.create({ data: { /* ... */ } });
  } catch (e) {
    console.error(e);
    return { error: 'Failed to create post' };
  }
  redirect('/posts'); // outside try/catch, throws cleanly
}
```

If you must catch other throws, re-throw any error whose message matches `NEXT_(REDIRECT|NOT_FOUND)` - see the catch-narrowing pattern in the `nextjs-error-handling` rule. Do NOT import `isRedirectError` from `next/dist/...` - it is not a stable public API.

## 13. Server Action without input validation **CRITICAL**

Server Actions are reachable as POST endpoints. `FormData` values are always strings. Never trust the shape.

```typescript
// BAD - assumes the form posted the right fields and types
'use server';
export async function updateProfile(formData: FormData) {
  await db.user.update({
    where: { id: formData.get('id') as string },
    data: { name: formData.get('name') as string },
  });
}

// CORRECT - validate with Zod, return errors as state
'use server';
import { z } from 'zod';

const UpdateProfileSchema = z.object({
  id: z.string().uuid(),
  name: z.string().min(1).max(80),
});

export async function updateProfile(_prev: State, formData: FormData) {
  const parsed = UpdateProfileSchema.safeParse({
    id: formData.get('id'),
    name: formData.get('name'),
  });
  if (!parsed.success) {
    return { errors: parsed.error.flatten().fieldErrors };
  }
  // ... DAL call (which re-checks auth + ownership)
}
```

`next-safe-action` and `zsa` are popular community wrappers. The shape they enforce is the same: parse, then act.

## 14. Server Action without authorization re-check **CRITICAL**

Page-level auth in a layout or `proxy.ts` does NOT protect the Server Action. Actions are independent POST endpoints reachable by URL. Always re-verify identity *and* resource ownership inside the action.

```typescript
// BAD - action trusts the page-level auth, never checks ownership
'use server';
export async function deletePost(postId: string) {
  await db.post.delete({ where: { id: postId } }); // IDOR: any logged-in user can delete any post
}

// CORRECT - verify session AND ownership
'use server';
import { verifySession } from '@/lib/dal';
export async function deletePost(postId: string) {
  const session = await verifySession();
  if (!session) throw new Error('Unauthorized');

  const post = await db.post.findUnique({ where: { id: postId } });
  if (!post || post.authorId !== session.userId) {
    throw new Error('Forbidden');
  }

  await db.post.delete({ where: { id: postId } });
}
```

See `nextjs-data-access-layer` rule for the cached `verifySession()` pattern.

## 15. Returning raw DB records from a Server Action **ERROR**

Action return values are serialized to the client. Return only what the UI needs - never raw DB rows with internal IDs, password hashes, soft-delete flags, etc.

```typescript
// BAD - returns the entire user row including passwordHash, isAdmin, audit fields
'use server';
export async function updateName(formData: FormData) {
  const user = await db.user.update({ /* ... */ });
  return user;
}

// CORRECT - return a DTO
'use server';
type UserDTO = { id: string; name: string; updatedAt: string };
export async function updateName(formData: FormData): Promise<UserDTO> {
  const user = await db.user.update({ /* ... */ });
  return { id: user.id, name: user.name, updatedAt: user.updatedAt.toISOString() };
}
```

DTOs are the project's API contract with the client. Don't leak the schema.

## 16. Fetching your own Route Handler from a Server Component **WARN**

Server Components run on the server. `fetch('/api/foo')` from inside one makes a wasteful HTTP round-trip to your own process. Call the data function directly.

```typescript
// BAD
export default async function Page() {
  const res = await fetch(`${process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_URL}/api/posts`); // round-trip
  const posts = await res.json();
  return <PostList posts={posts} />;
}

// CORRECT - call the underlying function directly
import { getPosts } from '@/lib/dal/posts';
export default async function Page() {
  const posts = await getPosts(); // direct call, no network
  return <PostList posts={posts} />;
}
```

Route Handlers are for external callers (webhooks, public APIs, mobile, AI streaming). Internal data goes through the DAL.

## 17. Mutation without revalidation **ERROR**

After a Server Action mutates data, the cached UI needs to refresh. `revalidatePath` for path-scoped, `revalidateTag(tag, profile)` for tag-scoped, or `updateTag(tag)` for read-your-writes within the same request.

```typescript
// BAD - data changes but the page still shows the stale cache
'use server';
export async function createPost(formData: FormData) {
  await db.post.create({ /* ... */ });
  redirect('/posts'); // /posts is still serving the stale cache
}

// CORRECT - bust the cache before navigating
'use server';
export async function createPost(formData: FormData) {
  await db.post.create({ /* ... */ });
  revalidateTag('posts', 'max');
  redirect('/posts');
}

// ALTERNATIVE - read-your-writes within the same response
'use server';
export async function createPost(formData: FormData) {
  await db.post.create({ /* ... */ });
  updateTag('posts'); // expires + refreshes inline
  return { ok: true }; // no redirect, UI sees fresh data
}
```

## 18. Missing `default.js` in a parallel route slot **ERROR**

Parallel routes (`@modal`, `@sidebar`) require a `default.js` for each slot. Without it, navigation to a route that doesn't define content for that slot triggers a 404 in v16 (was a soft warning in v15).

```typescript
// REQUIRED FILE STRUCTURE
app/
  layout.tsx           // accepts { children, modal } props
  page.tsx
  @modal/
    default.tsx        // <-- REQUIRED in v16
    (.)photos/
      [id]/
        page.tsx
```

```typescript
// app/@modal/default.tsx
export default function Default() {
  return null; // empty slot is fine, the file just has to exist
}
```

## 19. `next/legacy/image` import **WARN**

`next/legacy/image` was the v11 transitional adapter and is deprecated. Use `next/image`.

```typescript
// BAD
import Image from 'next/legacy/image';

// CORRECT
import Image from 'next/image';
```

## 20. `images.domains` config **WARN**

Replaced by `images.remotePatterns` in v15, fully deprecated in v16. `remotePatterns` is more precise (host + path + port + protocol).

```typescript
// BAD - next.config.ts
const config = {
  images: { domains: ['cdn.example.com'] },
};

// CORRECT
const config = {
  images: {
    remotePatterns: [
      { protocol: 'https', hostname: 'cdn.example.com', pathname: '/images/**' },
    ],
  },
};
```

## 21. `images.quality` value outside `images.qualities` **ERROR**

In v16 the `quality` prop on `<Image>` is coerced to the nearest value in `images.qualities` config (default `[75]`). A `quality={90}` falls back to 75 silently. Either configure `images.qualities` or stop hardcoding non-75 values.

```typescript
// CONTEXT - default config
// next.config.ts has no images.qualities, defaults to [75]

// BAD - silently coerced to 75
<Image src="/hero.jpg" alt="Hero" quality={90} width={1200} height={600} />

// CORRECT (option A) - widen the allowed qualities
const config = {
  images: { qualities: [50, 75, 90] },
};

// CORRECT (option B) - drop the prop, use the default
<Image src="/hero.jpg" alt="Hero" width={1200} height={600} />
```

## 22. Hardcoded `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` env for secrets **CRITICAL**

Any env var prefixed `NEXT_PUBLIC_` is inlined into the client bundle at build time. A secret with that prefix is shipped to every browser.

```typescript
// BAD - bundled into the client JS, visible in DevTools
const stripeKey = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_STRIPE_SECRET_KEY;

// CORRECT - server-only, never bundled
// (consumed from a Server Component, Server Action, or Route Handler only)
const stripeKey = process.env.STRIPE_SECRET_KEY;
```

Add `import 'server-only'` to the file that reads server secrets to throw at build time if a Client Component ever imports it.

## 23. `serverRuntimeConfig` / `publicRuntimeConfig` **ERROR**

Removed in v16. Use `process.env.*` directly. For runtime-read (i.e. read at request time, not build time), wrap the read in `await connection()` first to opt the segment out of static optimisation. `connection` is imported from `next/server`.

```typescript
// BAD
import getConfig from 'next/config';
const { serverRuntimeConfig } = getConfig();
const apiKey = serverRuntimeConfig.API_KEY;

// CORRECT
const apiKey = process.env.API_KEY;

// CORRECT (runtime-read, opt out of static optimisation)
import { connection } from 'next/server';
export async function getApiKey() {
  await connection();
  return process.env.API_KEY!;
}
```

## 24. `next lint` command **WARN**

Removed in v16. Run ESLint or Biome directly via `package.json` scripts.

```json
// BAD - package.json
{ "scripts": { "lint": "next lint" } }

// CORRECT
{ "scripts": { "lint": "eslint . --max-warnings=0" } }
```

Codemod: `npx @next/codemod@latest next-lint-to-eslint-cli`.

## 25. Custom `webpack` config without `--webpack` flag **ERROR**

Turbopack is the default bundler in v16. A custom `webpack` config in `next.config` causes `next build` to fail unless you explicitly opt in to webpack.

```typescript
// BAD - this fails next build in v16
const config = {
  webpack: (config) => { /* ... */ return config; },
};
```

```jsonc
// CORRECT (option A) - explicitly use webpack
// package.json
{ "scripts": { "build": "next build --webpack" } }
```

```typescript
// CORRECT (option B) - migrate the customization to turbopack config
const config = {
  turbopack: {
    resolveAlias: { /* ... */ },
    rules: { /* ... */ },
  },
};
```

## 26. `'use client'` library imported by a Server Component just for one prop **WARN**

When you put `'use client'` on a wrapper component and import it from a Server Component, the wrapper plus its entire transitive client-graph ships to every visitor. Push the boundary closer to the actual interactivity.

```typescript
// BAD - <Hero> is a Client Component just so the CTA can be onClick
'use client';
export function Hero({ title, ctaLabel }: Props) {
  return (
    <section>
      <h1>{title}</h1>
      <button onClick={() => track('cta')}>{ctaLabel}</button>
    </section>
  );
}

// CORRECT - Hero stays a Server Component, only the button is client
// hero.tsx (Server Component)
import { TrackedButton } from './tracked-button';
export function Hero({ title, ctaLabel }: Props) {
  return (
    <section>
      <h1>{title}</h1>
      <TrackedButton label={ctaLabel} />
    </section>
  );
}

// tracked-button.tsx
'use client';
export function TrackedButton({ label }: { label: string }) {
  return <button onClick={() => track('cta')}>{label}</button>;
}
```

## 27. React Context for auth/session in Server Components **ERROR**

React Context doesn't work in Server Components. A `<SessionProvider value={...}>` wrapping a Server Component child does NOT propagate. The server child renders without the context, producing wrong (or null) data.

```typescript
// BAD - context never reaches the Server Component child
'use client';
const SessionContext = createContext<Session | null>(null);

// Then somewhere:
<SessionProvider value={session}>
  <ServerDashboard /> {/* server child, no context */}
</SessionProvider>

// CORRECT - read session in the Server Component directly
import { verifySession } from '@/lib/dal';
export default async function ServerDashboard() {
  const session = await verifySession();
  if (!session) redirect('/login');
  return <Dashboard userId={session.userId} />;
}
```

For Client Components, use the React Context pattern - just make sure the provider wraps only Client Component children.

## 28. `error.tsx` wrapping a `layout.tsx` **ERROR**

`error.tsx` does NOT catch errors thrown by the sibling `layout.tsx` - it only catches errors from `page.tsx` and below. To catch layout errors, use `error.tsx` one segment higher, or `global-error.tsx` at the root.

```
// FILE STRUCTURE - what each error boundary catches
app/
  layout.tsx                  <-- root layout errors -> global-error.tsx
  global-error.tsx
  dashboard/
    layout.tsx                <-- this layout's errors -> caught by parent /app error.tsx OR global-error.tsx
    error.tsx                 <-- catches page.tsx + children's errors, but NOT the layout above it
    page.tsx
```

LLMs often place `error.tsx` next to a `layout.tsx` and expect it to catch layout-throwing code. It won't.

## 29. `cookies().set(...)` during render **ERROR**

Setting cookies during render is forbidden. You can only mutate cookies in a Server Action, Route Handler, or `proxy.ts`.

```typescript
// BAD - throws "Cookies can only be modified in a Server Action or Route Handler"
export default async function Page() {
  const cookieStore = await cookies();
  cookieStore.set('seen', '1');  // <-- forbidden during render
  return <div>...</div>;
}

// CORRECT - set the cookie inside a Server Action triggered by a form
'use server';
export async function markSeen() {
  const cookieStore = await cookies();
  cookieStore.set('seen', '1');
}
```

## 30. `useEffect`-based redirects from Client Components for auth gating **WARN**

```typescript
// BAD - flash of unauthenticated content
'use client';
import { useRouter } from 'next/navigation';
export function ProtectedPage() {
  const router = useRouter();
  useEffect(() => {
    if (!session) router.push('/login');
  }, []);
  return <Dashboard />;
}

// CORRECT - server-side redirect, no flash
import { redirect } from 'next/navigation';
import { verifySession } from '@/lib/dal';
export default async function ProtectedPage() {
  const session = await verifySession();
  if (!session) redirect('/login');
  return <Dashboard />;
}
```

## 31. Importing `Page` types from `next/router` **CRITICAL**

`next/router` is Pages Router only. App Router uses `next/navigation` (`useRouter`, `usePathname`, `useSearchParams`, `redirect`, `notFound`).

```typescript
// BAD
import { useRouter } from 'next/router';

// CORRECT
import { useRouter } from 'next/navigation'; // client
import { redirect } from 'next/navigation';  // server
```

`router.push` / `router.replace` still exist on the App Router `useRouter`. `router.events` and `router.query` do NOT - those were Pages Router.

## 32. Sass tilde imports `~bootstrap/...` **WARN**

Turbopack does not support webpack's tilde-import resolver. Use the standard relative or `@import` path.

```scss
// BAD - works under webpack, not Turbopack
@import "~bootstrap/scss/bootstrap";

// CORRECT
@import "bootstrap/scss/bootstrap"; // resolved via node_modules
```

If you must keep webpack, run with `next build --webpack`.

## 33. Sync `id` in `generateImageMetadata` callbacks **ERROR**

In v16, the `id` parameter passed to image-metadata callbacks (used with `generateImageMetadata`) is a Promise. Pre-v16 it was a string.

```typescript
// BAD - v15 shape
export default function OG({ id }: { id: string }) {
  return new ImageResponse(<div>{id}</div>);
}

// CORRECT - v16
export default async function OG({ id }: { id: Promise<string> }) {
  const resolved = await id;
  return new ImageResponse(<div>{resolved}</div>);
}
```

`params` in the same callback was already async in v15; v16 brought `id` into line.

## 34. `experimental.taint` flag for `taintUniqueValue` / `taintObjectReference` **SUGGESTION**

`taintUniqueValue` and `taintObjectReference` from `react` (not `next`) are powerful guards against accidentally passing server-only secrets to Client Components. They are still gated behind `experimental.taint` as of v16.2.x - verify against the changelog for your installed version before enabling. Use them for high-stakes values: session tokens, API secrets, full user rows.

```typescript
// USAGE
import { experimental_taintUniqueValue as taintUniqueValue } from 'react';
import 'server-only';

const token = process.env.STRIPE_SECRET_KEY!;
taintUniqueValue(
  'Do not pass the Stripe secret key to the client',
  process, // or any owner object
  token
);
```

If the value ever reaches `JSON.stringify` for a Client Component prop, React throws.
